<Layout title="Sanshin vs Shamisen: Why So Many Okinawans Call Their Instrument by the Wrong Name | Unmuting Ryukyu">

	<article>

		<!-- ARTICLE HEADER -->
		<header style="padding:72px 32px 56px;background:#1C2C4F;position:relative;overflow:hidden;border-bottom:4px solid #8B1D25;">
			<div style="position:absolute;inset:0;z-index:0;background:linear-gradient(135deg, #1C2C4F 60%, #0a0a1a 100%);"></div>
			<div style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:5px;height:100%;background:#8B1D25;z-index:2;"></div>
			<div style="position:absolute;right:-40px;bottom:-20px;font-family:'Shippori Mincho',serif;font-size:200px;font-weight:700;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.03);line-height:1;user-select:none;pointer-events:none;z-index:1;">三</div>
			<div style="max-width:840px;margin:0 auto;position:relative;z-index:2;">
				<div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:12px;margin-bottom:20px;">
					<span style="display:inline-block;background:#8B1D25;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;padding:4px 12px;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;">History & Identity</span>
					<span style="color:#8B9BB8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;">March 2026</span>
				</div>
				<h1 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:clamp(24px,4.5vw,40px);font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;line-height:1.25;">Sanshin vs Shamisen:<br>Why So Many Okinawans Call Their Instrument by the Wrong Name</h1>
				<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;font-style:italic;margin:0 0 16px 0;line-height:1.7;">They are cousins — not twins. One came first. And the confusion between them is not an accident. It is the fingerprint of colonization.</p>
				<p style="color:#8B9BB8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:13px;margin:0;">By <a href="/about/" style="color:#D4C9BC;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Shohei Toguchi</a></p>
			</div>
		</header>

		<!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
		<div style="padding:72px 32px 96px;background:#F0EBE3;">
			<div style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;">

				<!-- Opening -->
				<div style="border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding:24px 32px;margin-bottom:56px;background:#fff;">
					<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:19px;color:#1C2C4F;line-height:1.75;margin:0;font-style:italic;">"Ask an older Okinawan what instrument they play. Many will say <em>shamisen</em>. They are playing the sanshin. They have always been playing the sanshin. The word just got taken from them."</p>
				</div>

				<div style="font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;color:#4A3F3B;font-size:16px;line-height:1.95;">

					<!-- Section 1 -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">Which Came First?</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						The answer is clear, and it matters: <strong>the sanshin came first.</strong>
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						In the 14th century, the Ryukyu Kingdom was one of the great maritime trading nations of Asia. Its ships sailed to China, Japan, Korea, and Southeast Asia. Through this trade, a Chinese three-stringed lute — the <em>sanxian</em> (三弦) — arrived on Okinawan shores. Ryukyuan craftsmen transformed it: they replaced the body covering with python skin (<em>jabisen</em>), adapted the tuning, and built a new musical tradition around it. They called it the <strong>sanshin</strong>.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 40px 0;">
						Two centuries later, in the 16th century, the sanshin traveled from Okinawa to mainland Japan through Sakai merchants. On the mainland, it was modified again — the snakeskin was replaced with cat or dog skin, the neck was thickened, the sound made louder. The Japanese called their version the <strong>shamisen</strong>. It became central to kabuki theater, geisha culture, and Japanese classical music.
					</p>

					<!-- Timeline visual -->
					<div style="margin-bottom:48px;position:relative;">
						<div style="position:absolute;left:20px;top:0;bottom:0;width:2px;background:#D0C5BA;"></div>
						<div style="padding-left:52px;margin-bottom:32px;position:relative;">
							<div style="position:absolute;left:11px;top:4px;width:20px;height:20px;border-radius:50%;background:#8B1D25;border:3px solid #F0EBE3;box-shadow:0 0 0 2px #8B1D25;"></div>
							<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 6px 0;">14th–15th Century</p>
							<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:17px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 6px 0;">China → Ryukyu</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">The <em>sanxian</em> arrives via trade. Okinawan craftsmen adapt it into the <strong>sanshin</strong> with python skin. A new musical tradition is born.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="padding-left:52px;margin-bottom:32px;position:relative;">
							<div style="position:absolute;left:11px;top:4px;width:20px;height:20px;border-radius:50%;background:#1C2C4F;border:3px solid #F0EBE3;box-shadow:0 0 0 2px #1C2C4F;"></div>
							<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 6px 0;">16th Century</p>
							<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:17px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 6px 0;">Ryukyu → Japan</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">The sanshin travels to mainland Japan via Sakai merchants. Japanese craftsmen modify it — new skin, new neck, new name: <strong>shamisen</strong>.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="padding-left:52px;position:relative;">
							<div style="position:absolute;left:11px;top:4px;width:20px;height:20px;border-radius:50%;background:#8B1D25;border:3px solid #F0EBE3;box-shadow:0 0 0 2px #8B1D25;"></div>
							<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 6px 0;">1879 — The Turning Point</p>
							<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:17px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 6px 0;">Ryukyu → Okinawa Prefecture</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">The Meiji government abolishes the Ryukyu Kingdom by force. Okinawa becomes a Japanese prefecture. And the slow erasure of Ryukyuan culture begins — including what Okinawans called their own instrument.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<!-- Section 2 -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">The Year the Name Started to Disappear: 1879</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						In 1879, the Meiji government sent soldiers to Shuri Castle, the seat of the Ryukyu Kingdom, and forced the last Ryukyuan king, Shō Tai, to relocate to Tokyo. The Ryukyu Kingdom — which had existed for over 450 years — was dissolved overnight. Okinawa became a prefecture of Japan.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						What followed was a systematic campaign of assimilation known as <em>dōka seisaku</em> (同化政策). Okinawan children were punished for speaking <em>Uchinaaguchi</em>, their native language, in schools. They were made to wear wooden tags called <em>hōgen fuda</em> (方言札) as punishment — a public mark of shame for speaking their mother tongue. Everything Okinawan was positioned as inferior, backwards, something to overcome.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 40px 0;">
						In this context, the word <em>sanshin</em> began to give way to <em>shamisen</em> — the "proper" Japanese term. Not because people forgot. But because using the Japanese word was safer. It was survival.
					</p>

					<!-- Dark highlight box -->
					<div style="background:#1C2C4F;padding:36px 40px;margin-bottom:48px;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 16px 0;">The Hōgen Fuda</p>
						<p style="color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:16px;line-height:1.85;margin:0 0 16px 0;">In Okinawan schools under Japanese rule, children caught speaking <em>Uchinaaguchi</em> were forced to wear a wooden placard around their neck. The only way to remove it was to catch another student speaking the "wrong" language and pass the tag to them.</p>
						<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.85;margin:0;">This system turned children against each other. It was designed to make the native language feel like a burden — something to get rid of as fast as possible. The same logic applied to everything Ryukyuan: names, customs, and what you called your instrument.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Section 3: The actual differences -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">They Are Not the Same Instrument</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						If you put a sanshin and a shamisen side by side, the differences are immediate — and they go deeper than aesthetics.
					</p>

					<!-- Comparison table -->
					<div style="margin-bottom:48px;overflow-x:auto;">
						<table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:14px;">
							<thead>
								<tr>
									<th style="background:#1C2C4F;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;padding:14px 20px;text-align:left;width:30%;"></th>
									<th style="background:#8B1D25;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;padding:14px 20px;text-align:left;">Sanshin 三線</th>
									<th style="background:#1C2C4F;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;padding:14px 20px;text-align:left;">Shamisen 三味線</th>
								</tr>
							</thead>
							<tbody>
								<tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
									<td style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:14px 20px;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#4A3F3B;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Origin</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Ryukyu Kingdom (14th–15th c.)</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Japan, mainland (16th c.)</td>
								</tr>
								<tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
									<td style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:14px 20px;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#4A3F3B;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Body skin</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Python / snakeskin (<em>jabisen</em>)</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Cat or dog skin (varies by style)</td>
								</tr>
								<tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
									<td style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:14px 20px;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#4A3F3B;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Sound</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Warm, resonant, slightly rough</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Brighter, sharper, more projecting</td>
								</tr>
								<tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
									<td style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:14px 20px;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#4A3F3B;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Neck</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Thinner, lighter</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Thicker, heavier</td>
								</tr>
								<tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
									<td style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:14px 20px;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#4A3F3B;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Plectrum</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Finger bachi (index finger)</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Large flat bachi (whole hand)</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:14px 20px;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#4A3F3B;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Musical role</td>
									<td style="background:#fff;padding:14px 20px;color:#4A3F3B;line-height:1.7;">Folk songs (<em>minyo</em>), dance, ceremony</td>
