								</tr>
							</tbody>
						</table>
					</div>

					<!-- Section 4: global indigenous parallels -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">The Sanshin Is Not Alone: Indigenous Parallels Across Asia</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						What makes the sanshin's story even larger is this: across Asia, indigenous and minority peoples developed strikingly similar three-stringed instruments — often independently, often under the same pressures of cultural erasure from dominant neighbors.
					</p>

					<div style="display:grid;gap:2px;background:#D0C5BA;margin-bottom:40px;">
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;">
							<div style="display:flex;align-items:baseline;gap:12px;margin-bottom:10px;">
								<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;white-space:nowrap;">China / Silk Road</p>
								<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho',serif;font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0;">Sanxian 三弦</p>
							</div>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">The direct ancestor of the sanshin. Itself descended from Central Asian lutes that traveled the Silk Road. The chain of influence runs from the steppes of Mongolia all the way to Okinawa — one continuous thread of human music-making across thousands of miles.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;">
							<div style="display:flex;align-items:baseline;gap:12px;margin-bottom:10px;">
								<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;white-space:nowrap;">Vietnam</p>
								<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho',serif;font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0;">Đàn tam</p>
							</div>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">A Vietnamese three-stringed lute with snakeskin body — nearly identical construction to the sanshin. The Ryukyu Kingdom traded directly with Vietnam. Whether influence flowed both ways, or both drew from the same Chinese source, the parallels are undeniable.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;">
							<div style="display:flex;align-items:baseline;gap:12px;margin-bottom:10px;">
								<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;white-space:nowrap;">Taiwan Aboriginal</p>
								<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho',serif;font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0;">Indigenous string traditions</p>
							</div>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">The Ryukyu Islands and Taiwan sit just 110km apart at their closest point. For centuries, Ryukyuan fishermen and traders moved between the islands. Taiwan's Amis, Paiwan, and other Aboriginal peoples developed their own string instruments and oral music traditions — shaped by the same ocean that carried the sanshin.</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;">
							<div style="display:flex;align-items:baseline;gap:12px;margin-bottom:10px;">
								<p style="font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#8B1D25;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.15em;margin:0;white-space:nowrap;">Ainu — Hokkaido</p>
								<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho',serif;font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0;">Tonkori</p>
							</div>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;margin:0;">At the other end of the Japanese archipelago, the Ainu people of Hokkaido developed the tonkori — a five-stringed plucked instrument. Like the sanshin, it was suppressed under Japanese assimilation policy. Like the sanshin, it survived in hiding. Like the sanshin, it is being reclaimed today by a people asserting that their culture was never gone — only silenced.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<p style="margin:0 0 40px 0;font-style:italic;color:#4A3F3B;border-left:3px solid #D0C5BA;padding-left:20px;">
						The sanshin, the tonkori, the đàn tam — these instruments were never just music. For indigenous and minority peoples across Asia, string instruments have always been acts of identity. Something that could be hidden under a floorboard. Something that could not be translated into the colonizer's language. Something that survived.
					</p>

					<!-- Section 5: Today -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">Why Calling It "Sanshin" Is a Political Act</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						Today, there is a growing movement among younger Okinawans to reclaim the word <em>sanshin</em>. To correct grandparents who say <em>shamisen</em>. To explain to tourists — and to mainland Japanese — that these are two different instruments with two different histories, and that the sanshin came first.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						It is a small act. Saying one word instead of another. But language is where identity lives. The same logic that tried to replace <em>Uchinaaguchi</em> with Japanese, that hung <em>hōgen fuda</em> around children's necks, tried to replace <em>sanshin</em> with <em>shamisen</em>.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0;">
						When an Okinawan picks up their instrument and calls it by its true name, they are doing the same thing as everyone who played on March 4th. They are saying: <em>we were here before. We are still here. And we know what this is called.</em>
					</p>

				</div>

